# PART 1 — The Cast of Characters (as the backend actually defines them)

**World 1: Platform staff** (people who work for PayRole itself, not any customer)
Log in at `/platform-login`. Five possible roles, but in practice you'll only ever use
`super_admin`:

| Role | Can do |
|---|---|
| `super_admin` | Everything — bypasses all permission checks |
| `platform_admin` | Manage tenants, platform users, view system health/audit |
| `support_engineer` | Read tenants/users, view health, impersonate for support |
| `auditor` | Read-only: tenants, audit logs, system health |
| `devops` | System health/metrics/settings, audit read |

**World 2: Tenant staff** (people who work *at* a company using PayRole)
Log in at `/login`. Ten possible roles:

| Role | What they can actually touch (real backend permissions) |
|---|---|
| `super_admin` | Everything, tenant-wide — bypasses all permission checks (rare, "god mode" within the tenant) |
| `tenant_admin` | Users, workers, legal entities, compensation, pay elements, payroll (read/create/approve/reject/process/reverse), payslips, audit, import/export. **Cannot** edit the company's own tenant profile (that PATCH is `super_admin`-only) |
| `hr_manager` | Full worker/compensation/legal-entity read+write |
| `hr_officer` | Same area as hr_manager, narrower permission set |
| `payroll_manager` | Pay elements, worker pay elements, payroll read/create/**approve/reject**/process, payslips |
| `payroll_officer` | Same area as payroll_manager, narrower permission set — **no** approve/reject |
| `finance_manager` | Payroll **read-only** (cannot approve/reject — a common mix-up, see PART 4), payslip read/download, audit read |
| `auditor` | Read-only: audit logs, tax rules |
| `read_only` | Read-only: workers, payroll, payslips, legal entities, compensation, pay elements, tax rules |
| `employee_self_service` | **Only** `payslip:read` and `payslip:download`. That's it — no worker profile access, no bank details access, nothing else |

That last row matters a lot: an employee cannot view or edit their own worker profile
or bank details through this backend at all. Their whole world is payslips, plus the
universal `GET /users/me` and `PATCH /users/me/password` that every role gets.

**Gotcha worth knowing:** it's tempting to assume Finance approves payroll and Payroll
just submits it (classic maker/checker). The real backend does **not** implement that
split — `payroll_manager` holds both `PAYROLL_CREATE` and `PAYROLL_APPROVE`/
`PAYROLL_REJECT` (`roles.enum.ts`), while `finance_manager` holds neither. The frontend
used to gate the approve/reject buttons on `finance_manager` (matching the assumption,
not the backend), which meant finance managers saw nothing to approve and payroll
managers who *could* approve never saw the buttons either. Fixed to match the actual
permission grants — see PART 4.

